Encoding

In[21]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import OneHotEncoder
In[22]:
ohe=OneHotEncoder()
cat_cols=["Education","Living_with"]
enc_cols=ohe.fit_transform(df_cleaned[cat_cols])
In[23]:
# This line converts encoded categorical data into a proper Pandas DataFrame.
# Explanation
# 1. enc_cols.toarray()
# enc_cols is usually the output of OneHotEncoder.
# OneHotEncoder returns data in sparse matrix format (not normal table).
# .toarray() converts it into a normal numeric array.
# Example after encoding:
# Gender_Male	Gender_Female
# 1	0
# 0	1
# 2. ohe.get_feature_names_out(cat_cols)
# ohe = your OneHotEncoder object
# This generates proper column names.
# cat_cols = original categorical columns
# Example:
# If original column was:
# Gender
# It creates:
# Gender_Male
# Gender_Female
# 3. index=df_cleaned.index
# Keeps the same row index as original dataframe.
# So rows stay aligned when merging later.

enc_df=pd.DataFrame(enc_cols.toarray(),columns=ohe.get_feature_names_out(cat_cols),index=df_cleaned.index)
In[24]:
#Concatination
df_encoded=pd.concat([df_cleaned.drop(columns=cat_cols),enc_df],axis=1)

Analyze K Value

1.Elbow Method

In[36]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from kneed import KneeLocator

wcss=[]
for k in range(1,11):
    kmeans=KMeans(n_clusters=k,random_state=42)
    kmeans.fit_predict(X_pca)
    wcss.append(kmeans.inertia_)
In[37]:
#plot
plt.plot(range(1,11),wcss,marker='o')
plt.xlabel("K")
plt.ylabel("wcss")
Out[37]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'wcss')
In[38]:
#kneelocator
knee=KneeLocator(range(1,11),wcss,curve="convex",direction="decreasing")
optimal_k=knee.elbow
In[39]:
print("Best k value:",optimal_k)

Best k value: 4

2.Silhouette Score

In[40]:
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score
scores=[]
for k in range(2,11):
    kmeans=KMeans(n_clusters=k,random_state=42)
    labels=kmeans.fit_predict(X_pca)
    score=silhouette_score(X_pca,labels)
    scores.append(score)
In[41]:
#plot
plt.plot(range(2,11),scores,marker='o')
plt.xlabel("K")
plt.ylabel("silhouette_score")
Out[41]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'silhouette_score')

Combined plot

In[46]:
k_range=range(2,11)
fig,ax1=plt.subplots(figsize=(8,6))
#plot1
ax1.plot(k_range,wcss[:len(k_range)],marker="o",color="blue")
ax1.set_xlabel("K")
ax1.set_ylabel("WCSS")
#plot2
ax2=ax1.twinx()
ax2.plot(k_range, scores[:len(k_range)], marker="x", color="red", linestyle="--")
ax2.set_ylabel("SS")

plt.title("Elbow Method & Silhouette Score")
ax1.grid(True)
plt.show()
